05757nam a22012015i 9780691215853DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211994nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912158537 a10.1515/97806912158532doi  a(DE-B1597)566898  a(OCoLC)1243311620  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPA3015.D73b.M555 1994 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a880.9/3532201 aMiller, Patricia Cox, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDreams in Late Antiquity :bStudies in the Imagination of a Culture /cPatricia Cox Miller. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMythos: The Princeton/Bollingen Series in World Mythology ;v64700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tPart I IMAGES AND CONCEPTS OF DREAMING -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE Figurations of Dreams -- tCHAPTER TWO Theories of Dreams -- tCHAPTER THREE Interpretation of Dreams -- tCHAPTER FOUR Dreams and Therapy -- tPart II DREAMERS -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER FIVE Hermas and the Shepherd -- tCHAPTER SIX Perpetua and Her Diary of Dreams -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Aelius Aristides and The Sacred Tales -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Jerome and His Dreams -- tCHAPTER NINE The Two Gregorys and Ascetic Dreaming -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDream interpretation was a prominent feature of the intellectual and imaginative world of late antiquity, for martyrs and magicians, philosophers and theologians, polytheists and monotheists alike. Finding it difficult to account for the prevalence of dream-divination, modern scholarship has often condemned it as a cultural weakness, a mass lapse into mere superstition. In this book, Patricia Cox Miller draws on pagan, Jewish, and Christian sources and modern semiotic theory to demonstrate the integral importance of dreams in late-antique thought and life. She argues that Graeco-Roman dream literature functioned as a language of signs that formed a personal and cultural pattern of imagination and gave tangible substance to ideas such as time, cosmic history, and the self. Miller first discusses late-antique theories of dreaming, with emphasis on theological, philosophical, and hermeneutical methods of deciphering dreams as well as the practical uses of dreams, especially in magic and the cult of Asclepius. She then considers the cases of six Graeco-Roman dreamers: Hermas, Perpetua, Aelius Aristides, Jerome, Gregory of Nyssa, and Gregory of Nazianus. Her detailed readings illuminate the ways in which dreams provided solutions to ethical and religious problems, allowed for the reconfiguration of gender and identity, provided occasions for the articulation of ethical ideas, and altogether served as a means of making sense and order of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFilosofía antigua. 0aFilosofía antigua. 0aLiteratura clásica. 0aLiteratura clásica. 0aSueños en la literatura. 0aSueños en la literatura. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aAelius Aristides.  aApuleius.  aArtemidorus.  aAugustine.  aBerakoth.  aChrist.  aCicero.  aGalen.  aHermas.  aHomer.  aIrenaeus.  aJerome.  aLucian of Samosata.  aMacrobius.  aMontanism.  aNeoplatonism.  aOrigen.  aOvid.  aPausanias.  aPenelope.  aPlotinus.  aPlutarch.  aPorphyry.  aSelene.  aSocrates.  aThecla, St.  aVirgil.  aangels.  abinarism.  adaemons.  ademons.  aenupnion.  aeros.  afate.  aimagination.  aincubation.  amedicine.  aoneiros.  asemiotics.  avisio.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Univers